@AndaristRake @rawdeg @DavidKPiano @cpojer @itsdouges Usually the pattern is something like 

if (lastId.current !== id) {
  lastId.current = id;
  doSomething(id);
}

@rawdeg @DavidKPiano @AndaristRake @cpojer @itsdouges Synchronising case may happen “once” as a perf optimisation (empty deps). But it’s still synchronising.

Fire-and-forget may happen many times. (Eg whenever some prop changes.) But it’s still “inferring” something concrete happened and can’t run more often.

“Once” is irrelevant.

@jevakallio so a common way to protect against reentrancy is something like

let isRunning = false
function myAlgorithm() {
  if (isRunning) {
    return // or throw
  }
  isRunning = true
  try {
    // somewhere
    callUserCode()
  } finally {
    isRunning = false
  }
}

@jevakallio "reentrancy" is jargon for when you have 

function myAlgorithm() {
  // somewhere
  callUserCode()
}

and you don’t want user code to call myAlgorithm() from inside of it because myAlgorithm wasn’t written to handle two calls “at the same time”. that’s reentrancy
